### Configure Node.js Runtime in Next.js Route Segments

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/03-file-conventions/route-segment-config.mdx

Set the runtime environment for rendering pages and routes in Next.js. The 'nodejs' runtime is recommended and is the default. The 'edge' runtime is not supported for Cache Components. Use this export in layout, page, or route files.

```typescript
export const runtime = 'nodejs'
// 'nodejs' | 'edge'
```

```javascript
export const runtime = 'nodejs'
// 'nodejs' | 'edge'
```

--------------------------------

### Access Runtime Data with cookies() and headers() in Next.js

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/01-getting-started/06-cache-components.mdx

Demonstrates how to access runtime request data including cookies and headers in a Next.js async component. The component receives searchParams and accesses cookie and header stores asynchronously. This pattern requires wrapping in a Suspense boundary since runtime data cannot be statically prerendered.

```typescript
import { cookies, headers } from 'next/headers'
import { Suspense } from 'react'

async function RuntimeData({ searchParams }) {
  // Accessing request data
  const cookieStore = await cookies()
  const headerStore = await headers()
  const search = await searchParams

  return <div>Not in the static shell</div>
}
```

