### Check for Cookie Existence in Next.js Server Components

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/04-functions/cookies.mdx

This example illustrates how to check if a specific cookie exists using the `has()` method on the cookie store obtained from `next/headers`. It retrieves the cookie store asynchronously and then uses `cookieStore.has('theme')` to determine the presence of a cookie named 'theme'. This is useful for conditional rendering or logic based on client-side cookie availability.

```tsx
import { cookies } from 'next/headers'

export default async function Page() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies()
  const hasCookie = cookieStore.has('theme')
  return '...'
}
```

```jsx
import { cookies } from 'next/headers'

export default async function Page() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies()
  const hasCookie = cookieStore.has('theme')
  return '...'
}
```

